\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{setspace}
\setstretch{1.75}
\usepackage{graphicx} % Required for inserting images
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage[a4paper, total={7in, 9in}]{geometry}
\setcounter{MaxMatrixCols}{15}
\begin{document}

  \begin{Large}
   \textbf{Part (4):}
\end{Large} 
\\
Using the shape and temporal modes that we found in part (3), we now want to find the vectors $V_1$ and $V_2$ that represent the first two dimensions of the shape space. $V_i$ can be found by multiplying the $i$th singular value by the $i$th temporal mode, or
\\
\begin{center}
    $V_i = \sigma_i * \vec{v}_i$
\end{center}

\\
as the $V$ matrix found in part (3) represents the temporal modes. We then want to plot $V_1$ against $V_2$, which gives
\begin{figure}[h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.75\linewidth]{V1vsV2.png}
    \caption{$V_1$ vs $V_2$}
    \label{fig:enter-label}
\end{figure}
\\
It can be observed that these points form a closed loop. We want to find the best fitting low dimensional Fourier series $A$cos$(\theta)$ + $B$sin$(\theta)$ to describe the loop. To do this, we want to find the angle$(\theta)$ between the $V_1$ and $V_2$. This can be done with the MATLAB code

\begin{center}
$\vec{theta}$ = unwrap(atan2(V(:,2),V(:,1)))
\end{center}
\\
\pagebreak
\\
Now, we can use least squares to fit $V_i = A_i$cos$(\theta) + B_i$sin$(\theta)$ to find $A$ and $B$ for both $V_1$ and $V_2$. To perform this, we want to solve the least squares equation:
\\
\begin{center}
    $A^TA\vec{x} = A^TB$
\end{center}
\\

where $B = V_i$, $A = \begin{bmatrix}
    \vec{cos(\theta)} && \vec{sin(\theta)}
\end{bmatrix}$, and $\vec{x} = \begin{bmatrix}
    A_i && B_i
\end{bmatrix}^T$. Doing these calculations in MATLAB gives
\\
\begin{eqnarray}
    V_1 &\approx& 4.2925\cos(\theta) - 0.1475\sin(\theta) \nonumber
    \\
    V_2 &\approx& -0.1124\cos(\theta) + 4.2011\sin(\theta) \nonumber
\end{eqnarray}
\\
Plotting these best fit series against the data gives
\begin{figure}[h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.75\linewidth]{Fourier.png}
    \caption{Best Fit Fourier Series}
    \label{fig:enter-label}
\end{figure} 

\end{document}
